Sugar. Right at the tail-end there.

>>31712704
>>31712752
>>31713043
This is partly where setting compensates for either ambiguity in characterization, situations or skill sets where species plays into a significant role or stereotype, or any combination of the above. Undeveloped settings that do little to inform the plot, and characters wanting any development (or dialogue) that validates their species, are going to seem easily species-swappable. Readers notice that in our stories specifically because that's why they're reading in the first place: they want to see how skillfully we weave those animal characteristics into a coherent and relatable character. I greatly appreciate the writers who observe those details well.

Anonymous Sun 26 Jul 2020 13:00:09 No.31723917 Report
Quoted By:
Cont.

>>31712996
>>31713659
Also strong points (ones I agree with wholeheartedly), but they don't wholly relate back to that Anon's question as they more answer to personal preference than an objective scale of species swappability. He's interested in the prevalence of that trope in our writing.

Personally, the relationship, growth, and dynamism (or chemistry) between characters is what I'm really nibbling at my lip for when I'm deeply enthralled with a story, and species comes secondary to that, generally speaking. There are plenty of good stories where species isn't important outside the little details (scratches during rough sex, sense of smell, tail-play, etc). Overcoming that difference and finding a lifemate, a partner, a genuine n e e d for someone's touch and nearness, in someone so spectacularly different from oneself, is what I truly enjoy about /hmofa/ stories. If a story misses that mark, or doesn't build up to it well, it just doesn't excite me as much. It's wonderful to see the challenges, hardships, and barriers two partners will overcome when love blooms between them, and this takes it to a deliciously higher level. But that's why it's important to describe and express the challenges a female lead's species presents in an interspecies relationship with a human. However, that can only be done appreciably through dialogue, action, and body language with as little exposition as possible, and with subverting/overdoing stereotypes as little as possible.

During the Prohibition period in American history, it was illegal to produce, sell, and consume alcohol. Naturally, this was widely ignored and people still did all of that but now in secret areas where they wouldn't get caught. Hooch runners were smugglers who trafficked the goods to sellers. Fun fact: A lot of those same hooch runners would become stock car racers later as they had a lot of fun racing their cars on the roads and beaches when not running from the cops, and would eventually lead to the creation of NASCAR.
